s, as their convictions shaped how they were treated in prisons, their position in the labour market, and their access to rehabilitative resources.  With a focus on Imperial Germany's criminal policies and their afterlives in the Weimar era, Citizens into Dishonored Felons demonstrates how criminal punishment was never solely a disciplinary measure, but that it reflected a national moral compass that authorities used to dictate the rights to citizenship, honour and trust.  afunded by German Historical Institute Washington  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEx-convictsxSuffragezGermany. 0aFelon disenfranchisementzGermany. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh2 aGerman Historical Institute Washingtonefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099770540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781805391128zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781805391128zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781805391128/original  a978-3-11-099770-5 Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA